	Here Minsky's deep grounding in the prevailing Aristotelian culture reveals itself in the word "deliberate." The "other direction" Minsky favors is sometimes referred to as "expert systems" or Classical Computational Theory of Mind (CCTM)\'a0. Although these systems can become very complex, in principle they are composed of three systems: a set of rules, a set of facts, and an "inference engine" which applies the rules to the facts. At the root of any inference engine is a goal or set of goals, such as finding the problem with an engine that won't start, deciding whether a loan applicant should be accepted or rejected, or diagnosing a medical problem. \
